88fcc26d-3691-44f6-b027-12f34c9bcc61.0ff2cbbd-11ba-43f6-97eb-7153a4df9738.description=
This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR
    outFormat - The format of the output date/time.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR

Results\:
    returnResult - The date in the new format.

Responses\:
    success - The date was converted.
    failure - The date could not be converted.

Notes\:
    1. If default locale language from the Java environement is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-YYYY HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a".
    2. Note that the dateFormat and outFormat inputs are case sensitive. 'M' is used for months representation and 'm' for minutes.
    3. Within date and time pattern strings, unquoted letters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are interpreted as pattern letters representing the components of a date or time string. Text can be quoted using single quotes (') to avoid interpretation. "''" represents a single quote. All other characters are not interpreted; they're simply copied into the output string during formatting or matched against the input string during parsing. The following pattern letters are defined (all other characters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are reserved)\:

Letter	Date or Time Component			Presentation		Examples
G	Era designator				Text		AD
y	Year				Year		1996; 96
Y	Week year				Year		2009; 09
M	Month in year				Month		July; Jul; 07
w	Week in year				Number		27
W	Week in month				Number		2
D	Day in year				Number		189
d	Day in month				Number		10
F	Day of week in month			Number		2
E	Day name in week			Text		Tuesday; Tue
u	Day number of week (1 \= Monday, ..., 7 \= Sunday)	Number		1
a	Am/pm marker				Text		PM
H	Hour in day (0-23)			Number		0
k	Hour in day (1-24)			Number		24
K	Hour in am/pm (0-11)			Number		0
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12)			Number		12
m	Minute in hour				Number		30
s	Second in minute			Number		55
S	Millisecond				Number		978
z	Time zone				General time zone	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z	Time zone				RFC 822 time zone	-800
X	Time zone				ISO 8601 time zone	-08; -0800; -08\:00
Special case\:
unix	Unix timestamp			Number		1384326000

Examples for the date 2001-07-04 12\:08\:56 in U.S. Pacific Time\:

Date			DateFromat			DateLocaleLang	DateLocaleCountry
2001.07.04 AD at 12\:08\:56 PDT	yyyy.MM.dd G 'at' HH\:mm\:ss z		en		US
Wed, Jul 4, '01			EEE, MMM d, ''yy		en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235+0700	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSZ	en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235-07\:00	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX	en		US
1309781336			unix			-		-
88fcc26d-3691-44f6-b027-12f34c9bcc61.1bce7d12-ce87-4f1c-8076-216777dc9e3e.description=
Schedule Flow - Schedules a flow or updates an existing schedule of a flow.

Inputs\:
    host - The target host for your request. The host can also be given as a URL.
    username - The username to use when connecting to the Central service.
    password - The password to use when connecting to the Central service.
    port - The port the Central service is running on.
Default value\: 8080.
    protocol - The protocol used to communicate to the Central service.
Default value\: http
Valid values\: http, https.
    trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false.
Valid values\: true, false.
    trustKeystore - The path of the truststore file. It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
    trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore. Provide this input only if trustKeystore is not empty.
    flow - The UUID or the path of the flow to run.
Example\: /Library/Integrations/Amazon/S3/Buckets/Enumerate Buckets
    schedule - The id of the schedule to update.
    names - A delimiter separated list of names of flow inputs.
    values - A delimiter separated list of values of flow inputs.
    delimiter - The delimiter separating lists of names and values.
Default value\: , (comma).
    description - A description of this schedule. If this input is set then the provided value will be the "Schedule Name" in Central/Run Management/Scheduler and after the execution of the scheduled flow will appear as "Run Name" in Central/Run Management/Run Explorer. 
Example\: "Scheduled Flow Created By ..."
    enabled - Set false to create the schedule disabled. This input is case insensitive.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: true.
    startTime - The time to start running the flow either as minutes from now or as a date. Use the utility operations from "Date and Time" folder to pass valid startTime value.
Example\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT
Example\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT+0430 (4 hours, 30 minutes west of the Greenwich meridian).
    endTime - The time to end running the flow either as minutes from now or as a date. Use the utility operations from "Date and Time" folder to pass valid endTime value.
Example\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT
Example\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT+0430 (4 hours, 30 minutes west of the Greenwich meridian).
    timesToRun - The number of times to re-run the flow schedule. If empty, the number of times to re-run the schedule will be computed as (endTime - startTime)/repeatInterval. If -1 the flow will be scheduled to run indefinitely, otherwise this input must have a positive value.
    repeatInterval - Sets the time interval in minutes between schedule triggering. If empty, the operation will set it to 1 minute.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Thi is the primary output. The id of the schedule.
    flowUuid - The UUID of the flow. This can be useful if the flow input is the path of the flow.

Responses\:
    success - The schedule was created or updated.
    failure - Could not connect to central web service. Invalid inputs. Invalid flow path. The schedule ends before it starts. The schedule ends in the past.

Notes\:
1. "timesToRun" and "endTime" inputs are mutually exclusive.

88fcc26d-3691-44f6-b027-12f34c9bcc61.28491b2c-700a-45ec-9ea1-55c1daea01f8.description=
Changes the time represented by a date by the specified number of seconds. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale. Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
date - The date and time to modify, formatted as provided by Get Current Date and Time.
offset - The number of seconds to change date by.
localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. For example,  en or ja.
localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

returns\:
A new date and time, formatted the same as the input.

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully.
failure - Something went wrong.

Inputs\: _PROCESS_INSTANCE_ID - Process Instance Id _processInstanceState - Process Instance State (Use value from selection list CSA-ProcessInstance-State) Result\: _processInstanceState -Updated Process Instance State 88fcc26d-3691-44f6-b027-12f34c9bcc61.4f7a670d-6f7a-41dd-9390-06f42c5b0365.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
88fcc26d-3691-44f6-b027-12f34c9bcc61.598e1d07-c565-403a-bdca-42371d0d6b99.description=
Check the current date and time, and returns a java DateAndTime formatted string of it. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale.Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. For example,  en or ja.
localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Result\:
Current date and time.

Responses\:
success - Date/time retrieved successfully.
failure - Date/time could not be retrieved.

Input Values\: vm.requester.email - The email address from the prior step result htmldocument - THe email body text from the prior result 88fcc26d-3691-44f6-b027-12f34c9bcc61.d187efb4-d2c0-40c5-a661-068846635750.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
string1 - The first string.
string2 - The second string.
ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

responses\:
true - If the two strings are equal
false - If the two strings are not equal

88fcc26d-3691-44f6-b027-12f34c9bcc61.f9f324a9-667b-4614-85a0-33d03b0cddc7.description=
Performs a mathematical operation on two numbers or strings

Inputs\:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.
operation - The operation to perform (+ - * ^ / > < \=\= \!\= >\= <\=).

Responses\:
success -  The operation completed successfully. If a boolean operation, it evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.

Returns\:
The raw result of the operation, for boolean values this is true or false.

Returns\:
Field 1 - The first value. Here for compatibility
Field 2 - The second value. Here for compatibility
Field 3 - The operation. Here for compatibility
formatted_result - The formatted result of the operation, for boolean values this is true or false.
